le intersecting hierarchies of gender, age, enslavement, lineage, class, and other social roles. Saadia Yacoob offers a restorative reading of Islamic law, arguing that its intersectional and relational understanding of legal personhood offers a productive space for Muslim feminists to move beyond critique and instead think with and through the Islamic legal tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHanafitesxDoctrines. 0aIslamic lawxInterpretation and constructionvEarly works to 1800. 0aPersons (Islamic law)xHistory. 0aWomen (Islamic law)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Arabian Peninsula.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393813zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393813zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393813/original  a978-3-11-079135-8 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA